# File Bug

One bug per ticket. Dedup hard. Include source links.

## Target

{{#IF_NOTION_BUGS}}
**Notion Bug Tracker DB**: `{{NOTION_BUG_DB_ID}}`
{{/IF_NOTION_BUGS}}
{{#IF_GITHUB_ISSUES}}
**GitHub Issues**: `{{GITHUB_REPO}}`
{{/IF_GITHUB_ISSUES}}

## Workflow

1. **Load existing bugs** (open + in-progress) into context. Do not query per-bug — load all upfront.
2. **Dedup semantically.** If the new report matches an existing bug (same root cause, even if worded differently), add a comment to the existing one. **Do not file a duplicate.**
3. **Confirm assignee** with {{USER_PREFERRED_NAME}} if non-obvious.
4. **Build the ticket**:
   - Title: one-line behavior summary
   - Body: steps to reproduce, expected vs actual, source links (Slack thread, email, etc.)
   - Severity: P0 / P1 / P2 / P3
5. **File**.
6. **Confirm** with one-line in chat: ticket URL + title.

## Hard rules

- **Never file without source links.** A ticket without context is wrong.
- **Skip auto-filed bugs** (anything posted by automation pipelines, MCP bots, or other bots) — those usually already exist as tickets.
- **Dedup is semantic, not exact-match.** When in doubt, comment on the existing bug.

## Suppression

```bash
python3 {{WORKSPACE_ROOT}}/skills/note-management/scripts/directives.py check "<bug summary>" --scope file-bug
```
If matched (e.g. {{USER_PREFERRED_NAME}} flagged this as not-a-bug), don't file.
